segments.text: And now from the University of Chicago Institute of Politics and CNN, the AX files with your
host David Axelrod.
I've had the great pleasure over the last three years on election nights and debate
nights to sit on a CNN panel next to Gloria Borger, the network's chief political analyst.
And one of America's great veteran political journalists.
I sat down with Gloria the day after the midterms last week to talk about the results, but also
to talk about her remarkable career as one of the real pioneers among women in political
journalism.
Here's that conversation.
Gloria Borger, good to see you on a eventful week.
We're recording this the day after the midterm elections.
And I'm going to get to all of that, the sacking of the Attorney General and all of
that news because there's no rest for the weary.
But I want to talk a little bit about your own journey first.
Starting in New Rochelle, which as I remember was where Rob Petrie and Laura Petrie lived
in the Dick Van Dyke show.
So your quintessential suburban community in New York, tell me about your folks in New
Rochelle.
So I actually was born in the Bronx.
And when my father opened an air conditioning television store with his brother, we moved
to the suburbs, we moved to Dourchela, New York, but we lived in an apartment building,
never lived in a house.
My mother was a homemaker and my father commuted into the city every day.
I went to public schools, culminating in the wonderful New Rochelle High School, which was
a very large high school.
I think my graduating class had six or seven hundred kids, very diverse.
And it burned down my senior year.
Oh my.
There was an arsonist, actually my junior year, and then my senior year we went to school
in trailers.
And I actually just went back to New Rochelle High School to speak to the students there.
And it was a phenomenal experience for me because it's now 2,500 kids, all kinds of
education from kids who end up at Harvard to special vocational training.
It's just an amazing place.
So it was a wonderful place to go to high school.
New Rochelle back then was probably not terribly diverse, right?
It actually was.
It actually was.
It was divided by one road in town, but it actually was a pretty diverse high school.
And my friends were black and white, which for those days, and I'm an old lady, was kind
of amazing.
And so that's how we grew up.
And there were a lot of private schools around, but we couldn't afford it.
And I'm glad I didn't go, actually.
Now is politics discussed in the house?
Politics was not a big issue in my house.
My parents were Democrats, were Democrats, and it was just kind of assumed.
But no, not really.
Issues were discussed.
Local issues were discussed.
My mother was very involved.
But politics, per se, not so much.
I was the editor of my high school newspaper.
You'll be surprised to learn.
And so I was very involved with the politics of my high school.
But at home, it was sort of much more traditional than the way my kids grew up in Washington,
D.C., where politics was discussed nonstop.
And you were the editor of the newspaper.
What drew you to that?
What drew you to journalism?
I don't know.
I think I've always been kind of a gossip, and I like to ask questions.
The Huguenot Herald was what it was.
And we put it out, I think, every couple of weeks.
And so it was my great experiment because I loved it so much in high school.
I knew.
And it was crazy that early on.
But I just loved the reporting.
And I loved the writing.
And I loved causing the faculty to get upset with what we were doing.
So nothing's really changed.
And I went to college.
I was editor of my college paper.
So I kind of stuck with that.
And my husband always says to me, you're so lucky because you knew what you wanted to
do from day one.
I'm not sure I did.
But I liked it.
And I still do.
Speaking of diversity, you brought some to Colgate, where you went to school as like
an all-male preserve.
Right.
I was in the very first class of women.
I'm the oldest living female graduate of Colgate University.
So I was in the first class of women there.
And that's a bold move.
It was.
Well, I loved the school.
I was afraid of being a member of the first class.
I actually wanted to go to Princeton, but I didn't get in.
So Colgate was my second choice.
And happily, I ended up there.
But it was a very strange thing.
When you think back on it, and I've talked to a lot of women at Colgate about it since,
and Colgate is now 51% female, they prepared for us by putting plastic flowers in the
urinals in the men's bathroom.
And they gave us irons and ironing boards.
And I remember my father turning to my mother and saying, I'm not going to leave her here.
Do you?
Now, the other night we were sitting together on election night, and you saw all of these
women really were a big part of the story.
A whole class, new class of women coming to the house.
There were three or four women elected governors.
And women really driving the story that women voters in, particularly in suburban areas.
And women candidates, he's generally.
So I ask you this in the context of your own experience.
I mean, how did you process that?
Well, I love it.
I always think people turn to women when they need the mess cleaned up in many ways, works
that way in my house.
And I think that now people are turning to women because they are different, and they
are authentic.
And they provide something new.
And I think that when you see a hundred women now in Congress, it's very exciting.
I mean, I go back long enough to recall when women could not wear pants on the floor of
the Senate, when there was no ladies bathroom outside the Senate chamber.
I remember standing on the floor of the convention when Jerry Ferraro was nominated.
For vice president, 84 and getting chills because I thought this is the beginning of
something, only it really wasn't.
But, but things never go in a straight line.
Exactly, exactly.
But I remember at that moment thinking this is different, this is the beginning of something
and being disappointed time and time again.
And not only in politics, obviously, but in every career.
So to see this happen in politics is really exciting.
The challenge now is to not judge women by a different standard.
Yeah, you know, it's interesting.
I got a note, kind of an angry note from a friend of mine, very, very powerful woman
in business who said, how can you call it the year of the woman when, you know, two
women senators were defeated.
But the fact is part of becoming, of integrating women into the political processes that they're
going to win and they're also going to lose.
And there were obviously there's an, there'll be another additional woman senator who come
in this year because of what happened in Arizona, Nevada, a woman got elected.
But it would, the more it becomes not unique, I think is progress for the country.
The thing about these women candidates who came in, so many of them were first time candidates,
first time politicians.
From the military, a lot of them?
Yeah.
Yeah, they had credentials.
It was Abigail Spannberger from the CIA.
Right.
No, it was, I have to tell you, I've been brooding about the fact that I think in our own little
panel last night, there was a rush to sort of kind of, a rush to judgment about what
was going to happen last night.
It turned out to be a pretty inspiring night from the standpoint of 114 million people
voted.
These women and not just these women, but all over the country, these stories of people
who stepped up and said, you know what, I'm not going to sit on the couch.
I'm going to get involved.
I think, and even these people who lost, you know, Beto Rourke was an inspiring story.
He'll be back.
He will be and may be sooner than we think there's an awful lot of pressure on him to
take his act national.
You know, I think Donald Trump today in his press conference tried to make it seem as
if he was just fine with the Democrats taking back the house.
Yeah, we had.
Yeah, he tried to make it sound that way, but then he made it clear he wasn't fine.
He wasn't fine with it.
He doesn't want them exercising their oversight.
Right.
And he threatened to retaliate against them.
And of course now with Jeff Sessions resigning or being fired actually, they're going to investigate
it.
I thought Ron Kline, my old White House colleague, wrote a good column in the post today in which
he said he thought Democrats should spend the first hundred days working on legislation
to address some of these concerns about health care and other issues that their constituents
voted for them to deal with.
And I agree with that, but they may be forced to act more quickly because if it looks like
and it does look like the president's doing an end run.
Well, Nancy Pelosi was very clear.
I mean, you know, immediately Donald Trump said, effectively, I can't work with you if
you decide to do your job, which is to oversight.
And Nancy Pelosi said, whatever we do, we'll do it the right way and in our own time.
And you can be sure it'll be organized.
And it's going to be, you know, it's going to be within the within the rules.
And so I think Ron is right.
And I think and Pelosi pointed out, look, there are things maybe we can work together
on like preexisting conditions, for example, pharmaceuticals, drug prices, infrastructure,
get those things done because their constituents care about that, about drug prices.
But you can walk and chew gum at the same time.
Yes.
I don't think Donald Trump can because he can't compartmentalize.
And so, and we saw that today.
So I think that she will try and do it, but there's no doubt in my mind that some point
is just going to collapse.
As long as we're on the subject, what of Pelosi?
You know her very, very well.
I know her well.
You know, I there is this conundrum for some of these new members because they campaigned
and said they weren't going to vote for her.
And now they're here.
Right.
And there's a caucus.
It's no one knows who you voted for.
Right.
Well, you know the old Mo Yudal thing?
I want to thank the six, the 120 people who committed to vote for me in the 60 who actually
did.
Yeah.
Yeah.
But I mean, that's true.
But I think a lot of them pledged not to vote for her on the floor of that house.
I mean, tell me about her as a.
I look, I think Nancy Pelosi and David, you know this better than I do because you went
through the health care war without Nancy Pelosi.
When it happened.
Right.
When it happened.
Right.

She understands she's transitional.
She's 78 years old.
She gets it.
Wouldn't you want her on your side?
If running if you've got to bring generations together and try and get legislation through

She was your guide dog.
Right.
Listen, her determined the president's determination was matched only by hers.
And there was a period of time after Ted Kennedy died and after Democrats lost a special
election in Massachusetts when it looked like health care, health reform was dead.
And she and the president and Harry Reid quietly mapped out a strategy to revive it
and pass it.
And she had to work very, very hard to get her caucus to go along with it because they
had to accept a Senate bill that they didn't want because the Senate was not going to vote
again on this.
And it was, it was, I have no, listen, there's no one within those four walls better than
her at this process.
And she knows that too.
But it's the outward facing piece that these, and that's, it's, it's, it's going to be

So we'll, we'll see how that goes.
Yeah.
Well, um, Rahm Emanuel always says about Pelosi.

She's a dellisandro.

And she, she knows how to count.
She does.
She does.
And, and had a service, the needs of all of her members and understanding what they,

I see the need.
I see the problems of the members, but they're going to have a hard time finding someone.
Yeah.
Who's the natural replacement?
Right.
There is an any.
It was going to be Joe Crowley.
He's gone.
Gone.

Uh, you, you went on a fellowship.
Yes.
Study the British press.
That must have been an experience.

Yeah.

That was tough.
That's good.

Right.
Right.

We should explain because there are people who won't know that Jack Germant was a legend

I mean, there was a core, the boys on the bus from, uh, from the, that famous book in

on doors and maybe the doors of a few saloons.
Maybe.

New Hampshire and knocking on some doors?
What?

hired me and took a shot on this kid and, uh, Mary McGrory was, it was a columnist at
the Washington Star.
And she would travel with us.
And Germant was, it was just amazing to work with him because he would, it was at a time
when you covered politics, when you went down to the bar at night and the candidate would
actually come down and have a drink with you.
Yes.
And there was such a thing as off the record.
Right.
Which does not exist anymore.
Right.
Yeah.
And there are no more relationships.
And Germant was sort of a master at that.
And the candidates, what stunned me as this young baby reporter was the candidate, like
whether it was Mondale or whoever it was, would ask Germant what he was hearing and
was he doing okay?
Yeah.
And, and they would, they would have conversations not only about policy, but about what was going

And it was, so it was, it was amazing to learn from somebody like Germant who, who knew the
macro politics, but also the micro politics.
And there weren't a lot of us women at that time.
I mean, now I would say political journalism is over half female if I had to guess.
But there weren't a lot.
Right.
And, and for Jack to sort of open the door to a bunch of us, Maureen Dowd.
Yes.
Was your fellow at the Washington Star?
Yeah.
And so we, we were able to learn from these guys and they were, they were terrific to
us.
They just couldn't have been better and more welcoming.
And so it was an, these experiences kind of got me into political reporting.

Right.
Would you like to cover education?
And I said, no, no, not really.
And they said, well, that's how you'll get your start.
So instead I covered, I said, I don't really want to cover education.
And I said, well, the only place we can put you is in Prince George's County covering
the county politics.
And I said, great.
I'll go there.
So I drove 45 minutes every day in a car, a little old car provided by the Washington
Star that broke down.
And then I covered that and then I covered the Annapolis legislature.
And so I got into politics kind of through the, the back door until German kind of brought
me on the more national scene.
Part of that whole idea of shuttling off the young female reporter to the education
beat was the fact that these were male preserves these, I mean, I grew up in a newsroom at
a, you know, about the same time.
And so you must have, you mean, we're in the me too era now.
The things that, the things that are now, I think properly unacceptable were pretty commonplace
that they were.
And I, and you know, I just was chatting with a bunch of women my age about looking back

And it's interesting because, you know, I'm lucky enough never to have been harassed in

But you know, we all had experiences like my first boss whom I loved and it was now

Well, you know, I only hired you because I thought you had good legs, but you turned

And looking back, there's a lot of stuff we shouldn't have put up with, but we didn't

We didn't have confidence in the ways that women do now.
And I speak with my younger colleagues.

And we didn't have role models or mentors that was unheard of.

And so I'm so glad that women now can talk to each other about things that we never did

I had a conversation here with Judy Woodruff about her experiences being the weather girl

Totally.
What those days were like, you also did, you must have done sort of like we all did the

I'll never.

I did the copy.

Yes.

The star, yes.
